// This file was generated by Prisma, and assumes you have installed the following:
// npm install --save-dev prisma dotenv
import "dotenv/config";
import { defineConfig } from "prisma/config";

export default defineConfig({
  schema: "prisma/schema.prisma",
  migrations: {
    path: "prisma/migrations",
  },
  datasource: {
    url: process.env["DATABASE_URL"],
  },
});


It works because it solves the "missing engine" problem introduced in Prisma 7.
In previous versions (v5, v6), Prisma came bundled with a heavy Query Engine written in Rust. That engine knew exactly how to talk to your database. In Prisma 7, that engine was removed from the default client to make it smaller and faster.
Here is the breakdown of why that specific code works:
1. The "Driver Adapter" replaces the old Engine
Because Prisma 7 no longer has an internal engine to talk to PostgreSQL, it needs a "middleman."
pg (Pool): This is a standard Node.js library that manages connections to PostgreSQL.
PrismaPg (Adapter): This acts as the bridge. It tells Prisma, "Instead of using your own internal engine, use this pg pool to send queries to the database."
2. Explicit Configuration
The error you saw earlier (PrismaClientConstructorValidationError) was Prisma saying: "I'm ready to work, but I have no way to reach the database. Please give me an adapter or an Accelerate URL."
By passing super({ adapter }), you are explicitly handing Prisma the tools it needs to execute SQL.
3. Better Performance & Weight
By using this method:
Smaller Bundle: Your application doesn't have to carry around a massive Rust binary.
Edge Compatibility: This setup allows your NestJS app to run more easily on "Edge" environments (like Vercel or Cloudflare Workers) because it uses standard JavaScript database drivers.
A Quick Tip for Production
In your current code, every time PrismaService is instantiated, it creates a new Pool. In a standard NestJS setup (where services are singletons), this is fine. However, make sure your DATABASE_URL is correctly loaded in your .env file, or the Pool will fail silently before Prisma even starts.
Are you planning to deploy this to a serverless environment, or just a standard VPS/Docker setup?